{
  "text": "In contrast with space, between-individual variation in timing was significant for all main regions. This supports the hypothesis that birds may have individually optimized migration schedules [CITATION_1] . Battley [CITATION_2] recorded a high repeatability of the spring departure date (r \u00bc 0.83) for adult bar-tailed godwits. Similarly high repeatabilities were found for the onset of spring and autumn migration in this study (see also the electronic supplementary material, figure S1 ), but values varied across the different geographical regions. Such variation can be expected if conditions en route (weather and habitat) affect the progress of migration. This idea has been invoked to explain different phenological patterns at different latitudes in population- [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and individual-based [CITATION_5] studies. A larger withinindividual variation in timing in autumn is explained by variable annual breeding success [CITATION_6] . Interestingly, the order in which the birds departed was approximately the same for spring and for autumn ( figure 1b,c) , suggesting that the individual harriers migrate according to individual time schedules [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
